column11: The U.S. government warned in February 2016 that there is a serious risk of Iraq's Mosul Dam collapsing, potentially killing hundreds of thousands of people and knocking out a significant portion of Iraq's electricity supply (U.S. Embassy in Iraq, NY Times). Recommended Questions When will anti-Islamic State forces retake Raqqa? Will the government of Afghanistan and the Afghan Taliban participate in official talks before 1 March 2017? Iraq's Mosul dam has not collapsed. This question closed as "no" with an end date of 1 January 2018. See our FAQ to learn about how we resolve questions and how scores are calculated.

While the dam is ultimately destined to fail at some point due to the water soluble nature of the rock it is built upon, the Italian Trevi engineering firm is working to strengthen it - at least until the end of the year. The most sensitive period of time for fail is around April, when the water levels in the reservoir behind the dam are highest and put the greatest amount of pressure on the structure. However, this time period has already passed for this year.

Baghdad, 04 May 11:05 - (Agency Nova) - The Mosul Dam is working properly. Iraq's Minister of Water Resources, Hassan al Janabi, said in an official statement in which he reported that he had posted photos of the structure on Facebook's social network. "I am happy to show these images to the public," Janabi writes on his Facebook page, showing the opening of the dam spillway "which had been closed for 12 years." Janabi added that "procedures have been set up to allow the dam to reach a level of water rising above 319 meters, all in the presence of our Italian and US partners with our extraordinary team that hoisted the Iraqi flag (On the structure) ". Janabi explained that the level of the Tigris River will increase slightly next week, thanking the government team that is working with the engineers of the Italian firm Trevi to allow the dam to operate even under difficult circumstances. __________________________ COMMENTS: @Anneinak @Khalid : I did a lot of research on the Italian media on this, and then the news were right there in Facebook! Those warning of the dam's imminent collapse have themselves said that the repairs will simply only delay the problem and whilst this might be true it suggests that even they don't envisage the dam's collapse while maintenance is being carried out. The dam will likely hold, for now.

There are multiple news stories in different newspaper and web sites suggesting the dam could/might collapse at any time/in the spring. But as far as I can see they all seem be based on the same sources and the origin of these stories all seem to be link back to the same basic facts that were in the public domain many months ago. While this does not make them wrong, and it has always been said that the spring is the time that the dam contains the most water, a known "most dangerous dam in the world" seems much less likely to collapse because there are now so many people monitoring it. The dam most likely to collapse is the one that no one is monitoring and has a fault that no one has yet spotted.

The New Yorker story "Before the Flood" Jan 2 2017 is almost exactly the same as a story on the Mosul dam that was published several months ago. From my recollection of that earlier story it appears the situation now is as expected then i.e. the problems were well known the Italian engineers are at work, the US army is monitoring the dam, its badly located, the risk is highest in the Spring. My view is that with Mosul being a place that is the news for other reasons and the risk of the dam failing being so well known, then the risk of it failing in 2017 is lower that in was in 2014, 2015 and 2016 (when obviously it did not fail) many outside actors have a strong interest in ensuring the dam does not fail when the world is watching so closely. The example of the Teton dam in Idaho (see New Yorker article) does show the risk of building dams on unstable rock, but it failed within months of opening, the Mosul dam has survived for over 30 years.

Although Italy’s Trevi Group has been contracted to work on the Dam and reinforce the gypsum foundation there is an unfortunate high potential of the Dam eventually collapsing unless another solution is proposed and has the ability to be successfully carried out. The Dam was built on unstable ground that continually erodes and surveys have revealed sinkholes underneath. http://www.globalsecurity.org/military/world/iraq/mosul-dam.htm . It’s highest risk period is in April, May, and June when the melting snow causes rising water levels. Therefore if it happens before January 2018 it will likely be during these months.

Dams collapse. Not that often though. Dams also seem to collapse in the late fall and spring. Dams collapse for a variety of reasons. Poor maintenance, extreme inflow, earthquakes, geological instability, and poor construction a few reasons for Dam collapsing. Dams have also collapsed by deliberate means. The British in World War 2 bombed several Dams under code name Operation Chastise.

The dam is important to any administration of the country. It will be protected and necessary works will resume. Meanwhile, ISIS will be too busy defending its core positions in Mosul (town) to attempt any kind of meaningful attack on the dam again. Very unlikely that this happens prior to 2018.

While the position of the damn and its state are well known, actions by ISIS and the current efforts to repair will keep the dam functional before 1 January 2017. The coalition against ISIS should make moves to retake Mosul after the January of 2017. Here the chance occurs that ISIS moves to cause collapse of the damn if Mosul begins to fall. The likelihood of Mosul falling is very good within the next year, but most likely not until after the US election cycle. I feel that the US election cycle, current state of Iraqi Army units, and the conflicts in Syria and Turkey are preventing a move into Mosul until early 2017 at the earliest. Should this time table move up, US supported efforts, combined with the current Italian ones, should keep the dam intact until after 2018. However, ISIS is the factor which leads me to state if it is going to collapse, it will do so next year. Will take more looks at this as the news develops.

Work is already underway to repair the foundations of the dam. If sufficient repairs are carried out before winter when the winter snow melt will significantly increase pressure on the dam, the dam should hold up. This assumes the Iraqi government maintain possession of the dam from ISIS forces. Other factors include the repair schedule for the sluice gates which are currently not functioning. The probability of the dam giving way would significantly reduce if the sluice gates can be brought back online (the gates could be opened to reduce the back pressure). The risk of failure should significantly reduce once the repair schedule is underway.

Failure to maintain the dam; inadequate expertise; lack of material and no oversight.

In April, Trevi commenced setting up more than 450 Trevi technicians and staff in temporary housing to work at the site. The area is too dangerous for workers to live off site and travel to the dam. About the same amount of Italian military troops will also stay in the area to protect the workers from regional threats. It’s not the company’s first urgent repair job. The Trevi Group has almost 6 decades of experience in soil engineering and has done dam specialized maintenance work more than 170 times around the world. The US Army Corps of Engineers has been intimately involved, as well. A semi-confidential report issued earlier this year that was partially leaked through the Iraqi Parliament, gave the findings of a very bleak Corps assessment of the dam’s condition. The findings of that report were largely responsible for sounding the alarm on urgent maintenance needs. U.S. interests in the area--military, business, and political--have also been given an evacuation and contingency plan by the U.S. Embassy in the event that the dam fails catastrophically. http://www.businessreviewmiddleeast.com/leadership/548/The-race-to-repair-Iraqs-Mosul-Dam
